node.text:
JUST WOW 🤩

Grab the popcorn because @NASA’s Perseverance rover has sent us a one-of-kind video of her Mars landing. For the first time in history, we can see multiple angles of what it looks like to touch down on the Red Planet. Who knew the usually terrifying last minutes before landing on the Red Planet, otherwise known as Entry, Descent and Landing, could be so beautiful…

Click the link in @nasajpl bio to see more of the latest views from Jezero Crater: go.nasa.gov/3byJe5M

#CountdownToMars #Mars #RedPlanet #DareMightyThings #landing #EDL #EntryDescentAndLanding #space #NASA #JPL

node.text:
Check out how grains of sand arrange based on varying frequencies. This video highlights the study of visible sound vibrations, also known as Cymatics. Through cymatics we can understand that all physical objects (even our bodies) continuously vibrate at their own rates, and can be impacted by frequencies in our environment.

🎥: Ted Gioia (Twitter)

node.text:
Vegetables are alive. Just check out this cytoplasmic streaming in an onion cell. 🧅

The cell transports nutrients, proteins, sugars, and lipids along highway-like strands of the cell’s skeleton, or cytoskeleton. The big round thing is the nucleus in the onion cell, which holds the DNA.

🧫🔬 by @my.microscopic.world #Microscopic

node.text:
Stephenson 2-18 has recently become the biggest mf star in the known Universe. Larger than UY Scuti, Antares, Vy Canis Majoris, you name it.

The estimated radius is about 2,150 times that of the Sun, and the volume is 10 billion Suns. If Stephenson 2-18 replaced the Sun in the solar system, its photosphere would extend beyond the orbit of Saturn.

It would take earth's fastest jet over 500 years to travel around. It would take almost 9 hours at the speed of light.

Data from @planets_education .org

node.text: The discoloration between the masses of water in the video is actually showing light-coloured, sediment-rich freshwater meeting dark, salty ocean water. The water in the ocean has a much denser structure than the fresh water because of the salt, so the river water is unable to mix in. This same effect results in other phenomena, like rivers flowing backwards during high tide, brinicles and rivers that flow independently on the ocean floor.

node.text:
Next to ours, leafcutter ant society is the most complex society on earth. They build nests that can contain thousands of rooms and cover up to 0.5 km2, a feat that is necessary since a mature colony can contain more than eight million individuals.

But if they’re not eating the leaves that they carry home, what are they doing with them? Farming. Leafcutter ants use leaves as their fertilizer to grow their crop: fungus. They cultivate their fungal gardens by providing them with freshly cut leaves, protecting them from pests and molds, and clearing them of decayed material and garbage. In return, the fungus acts as a food source for the ants' larvae.

The ants are so sensitive to the fungi’s needs that they can detect how they are responding to a certain food source and change accordingly. This symbiotic relationship also benefits from a bacterium that grows on the ants’ bodies and secretes antimicrobials, which the ants use to protect their fungi.

🎥: @paulkaempf_macro
